  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Normalization:</strong> If short-term rates drop, client cash sorting will decline, directly boosting deposit levels and net interest margin.</li>
    <li><strong>TD Ameritrade Synergies:</strong> Full realization of cost synergies and cross-selling opportunities from the TD Ameritrade acquisition could drive margins structurally higher.</li>
    <li><strong>Asset Gathering:</strong> Schwab continues to gather net new assets at an impressive rate. Compounding market returns on these assets provide a strong tailwind to fee revenues.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Deposit Flight / Cash Sorting:</strong> A prolonged period of high short-term interest rates could continue to pressure deposit levels as clients seek higher-yielding alternatives.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Changes:</strong> Changes in regulations regarding payment for order flow (PFOF) or capital requirements for brokers could impact profitability.</li>
    <li><strong>Market Drawdowns:</strong> A severe bear market would drastically reduce assets under management, cutting directly into Schwab's core asset management and administration fees.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Is DCF the best way to value a financial stock like Schwab?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">DCF can be tricky for financials because cash flows are often obscured by balance sheet mechanics (e.g., changes in deposits or loans). However, Schwab generates significant fee-based revenue, making FCF a viable metric when normalized. Dividend Discount Models (DDM) or Price/Tangible Book Value are also commonly used alongside DCF.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate reflects the risk of the cash flows. The 10Y Treasury is at 4.18%. Financials possess unique duration and liquidity risks. A 9.5% WACC builds in an equity risk premium that acknowledges Schwab's sensitivity to interest rate movements and market volatility.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How did cash sorting impact Schwab?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Cash sorting occurs when clients move idle cash from low-yielding sweep accounts into higher-yielding money market funds. This reduces Schwab's low-cost funding base, forcing them to borrow at higher rates (like from the FHLB) to maintain their balance sheet, squeezing their Net Interest Margin.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

